<subSubSection pageId="106" pageNumber="502" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="106.[1446,2652,1117,2411]" pageId="106" pageNumber="502">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1447,1797,1983,2016]" pageId="106" pageNumber="502">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. The Saharan White-toothed Shrew is considered rare (although possibly locally abundant) with a declining population as indicated by fresh owl pellets in which they are now less common than they used to be. Live specimens were not collected for many years, being recorded in owl pellets throughout their distribution; however,five specimens were recently trapped in the Guelmim region. Climate change (i.e. desertification) has made some areas ofits distribution uninhabitable. Phosphate mines and possibly overgrazing might have significant effects on populations of the Saharan White-toothed Shrew, but additional research is needed to verify this.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
